API-Services-Microservices Landscape
•
Ecosystem
•
Current API definition evaluation will need to be done to see if the current way of defining an API will match with the future state of API inventory
•
In a complex enterprise environment, it is often confusing to differentiate between an API, a service, and a microservice, especially when the same component may be labelled differently depending on how it’s used. This leads to common questions around where to draw the boundaries and whether a single component can be considered an API, a service, or both in different contexts.
•
The environment typically spans on-prem and cloud deployments in a multi-cloud, hybrid model using platforms such as AWS and Azure. It includes SAAS solutions like Salesforce and ServiceNow, monitoring tools such as Datadog and Splunk, and internally built technologies such as NodeJS, Spring Boot, TIBCO BusinessWorks, or Pega. CI/CD tools like GitLab and Azure DevOps, centralized security via Okta, containerized workloads on Docker or Kubernetes, and APIs (as we know) managed through gateways like Apigee or Layer7 or MuleSoft (added at the edge for inbound and outbound traffic control) are all par to four ecosystems.
•
North-east traffic, refers to external interactions—inbound when external consumers access our APIs through gateways, and outbound when our applications call vendor-hosted APIs over the internet. South-west traffic represents internal-only communication between services within the organization, often running on Docker or Kubernetes or on applications hosting environments such as WebSphere application server. For containerized applications internal paths, a service mesh, such as Istio's may be added to manage service-to-service communication, security, observability, and traffic policies without embedding that logic into each service.
•
Given this complexity of layered and distributed environment, having clear and practical definitions for APIs, services, and microservices, and the traffic patterns they participate in is essential for consistent design, governance, architecture and communications across teams.

