API-Services-Microservices Dimension
•
Service (Service View - Capability dimension):
•
A logical business or technical capability.
•
A Service may exist without any API
•
A service may be implemented without microservices architecture.
•
If you are talking about “what business/technical function does it provide?”→ it’s a service.
•
API (API View - interface dimension):
•
A well-defined contract for interaction
•
Every API is backed by a service. If there is an API, means some service exists.
•
Not every service is exposed via an API.
•
If you are talking about endpoints, contracts, schemas→ it’s an API.
•
Microservice (Microservice view – Architecture dimension):
•
A service implemented using microservice architecture principles
•
Every microservice is a service
•
Many services are not microservices e.g., shared platforms, SaaS, workflows, monoliths)
•
If the deployable unit is independently scalable and deployable → it’s a microservice.
Summary: A microservice is a way to implement and operate a service; an API is how that service is accessed.

API (Interface Contract) Definition
Definition: A versioned, documented interface that defines how a capability is accessed by API client.
Key API Criteria:
•
Explicit contract (e.g., OpenAPI, GraphQL SDL, gRPC proto, event schema)
•
Authentication/authorization policy (e.g., OAuth2/OIDC via Okta, mTLS)
•
Versioning strategy (e.g., URI version, header, or schema version)
•
Lifecycle: design → publish → deprecate → retire, with consumer communication
•
Discoverability via API catalog and/or gateway (Apigee, Layer7, MuleSoft)
•
Non-functional policies enforced (rate limits / quotas, payload size, logging, PII handling, routing rules, security policies, transformation etc. (no business logic)
Note:
•
An API has deployable middleware code; it is the contract exposed by one or more services.
•
API is like a class definition, schema definition, template etc., that describes about input, output, endpoints etc. Once you create class to get an instance (which is runtime), that becomes service.

Service (Business Capability) Definition
Definition: A service implements a business capability which defines a stable, high-level function or capacity to deliver value.
Key Attributes:
•
Named by capability (e.g., Identity federation, Payment Processing, Customer Profile etc.)
•
Clear ownership (team, on-call, escalation path, SLA)
•
Interface(s): One or more APIs or events.
•
Boundary: well-defined inputs/outputs and data stewardship
•
Lifecycle: roadmap, change management, deprecation, incident postmortems
Note: A service may be implemented as a monolith, a microservice, a workflow (Tibco/Pega), or via SaaS (Salesforce/ServiceNow). The term reflects responsibility, not implementation.

Microservice (Architectural & Operational Style): Definition
Definition: A service implemented as an independently deployable and operable unit, typically containerized and orchestrated.
Key attributes:
•
Independent deployment (no lock-step releases with other services)
•
Owns its data (private schema or bounded-context ownership
•
Loose coupling (contacts stable; changes don’t cascade
•
Operational autonomy (separate CI/CD, scaling, rollback)
•
Runtime isolation (e.g., Docker, Kubernetes on AKS/EKS/on-prem)
•
Observability (metrics, logs, traces;)
Note: Exposing an API does not make a component a microservice. Independence and Operability do.

